text:
The IF Statement
The basic structure of a conditional statement:
if (condition) {
  // code to run if condition is true
}

IF Statement Example
function draw() {
  fill(0);  // default black fill
  background(220);

  // if cursor is on right half of canvas 
  if (mouseX &gt; width/2) {
    fill(255, 0, 0);  // red fill
  }

  circle(mouseX, mouseY, 50);
}
The circle turns red when the mouse is on the right half of the canvas. See it live!

The ELSE Statement
Use else when you want to do something when the condition is false:
if (mouseX &gt; width/2) {
  fill(255, 0, 0);    // red on right side
} else {
  fill(0, 0, 255);    // blue on left side
}
See it live!

Multiple Conditions with ELSE IF
Use else if to check multiple conditions in sequence:
if (mouseX &lt; width/3) {
  fill(255, 0, 0);        // red - left third
} else if (mouseX &lt; 2*width/3) {
  fill(0, 255, 0);        // green - middle third  
} else {
  fill(0, 0, 255);        // blue - right third
}
See it live!

Complex Example

if (mouseX &gt; width/2 && mouseY &gt; height/2) {
   fill(255, 0, 0);      // red - bottom right
} else if (mouseX &gt; width/2) {
   fill(0, 255, 0);      // green - top right
} else if (mouseY &gt; height/2) {
   fill(0, 0, 255);      // blue - bottom left
} else {
   fill(255, 255, 0);    // yellow - top left
}
The && operator means “AND” - both conditions must be true.

Built-in Boolean: mouseIsPressed
P5.js provides mouseIsPressed - a boolean that tracks if the mouse is currently being held down.
function draw() {
  if (mouseIsPressed) {
    background(255, 0, 0); // red when pressed
  } else {
    background(0, 0, 255); // blue when not pressed
  }
}

Creating Your Own Boolean Variables
You can create your own boolean variables to track any state:
let buttonPressed = false;
let lightOn = true;
let gameOver = false;

Toggling Boolean States
Use mousePressed() to toggle your boolean variable:
function mousePressed() {
  // Toggle the boolean value
  buttonPressed = !buttonPressed;
}
The ! operator flips the boolean value: - !true becomes false - !false becomes true

Boolean Logic in Conditionals
Booleans work perfectly with if statements:
if (gameStarted) {
  // run game code
}

if (!gameOver) {  // if NOT game over
  // continue playing
}

if (playerAlive && hasAmmo) {  // AND logic
  // player can shoot
}
